{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496504"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:48:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:48:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1370"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1370"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.7,0.16,0.06,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1370"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55948"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1370"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1370"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41497"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"725"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3332"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3528"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12329"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55948"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a one-day history of right upper quadrant pain. She otherwise feels well but expresses concerns about her kidneys as her sister has just started peritoneal dialysis for an unknown kidney disease. She denies any episodes of fever, haematuria, or dysuria. She has not been sexually active for the last six months. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination shows no abnormalities. Ultrasound reveals a hypoechoic lesion but the interpretation is hindered due to poor image quality. A CT scan of the abdomen is arranged (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Retroperitoneal sarcoma","Renal cyst","Renal cell carcinoma","Angiomyolipoma","Nephroblastoma"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a single simple \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal cyst\u003C/strong\u003E. The CT scan shows a large cyst at the lower pole of the right kidney. Renal cysts are very common and most are found incidentally on cross-sectional imaging. They account for 65-70% of kidney masses identified on imaging and are more common in people over 50 years old. Men are more commonly affected. The vast majority of simple renal cysts require no treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to distinguish simple cysts from multiple (polycystic) or potentially malignant lesions. Simple cysts tend to be large, unilateral, solitary, and have well-defined features. In comparison, genetically acquired or malignant cysts tend to be smaller, multilocular or multilobular, and present in greater numbers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eretroperitoneal sarcoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare malignant tumour that arises in the retroperitoneal space. They are often large at presentation and can cause non-specific symptoms like abdominal pain or fullness. However, the CT scan in this case clearly shows a cystic lesion arising from the kidney, making a retroperitoneal sarcoma unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn CT, thickened or irregular walls or septa of a mass paired with enhancement post-contrast are suggestive of malignancy such as \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E. Although uncommon, the typical \u0022RCC triad\u0022 (flank pain, hematuria, and a palpable abdominal renal mass) is also not present. The CT scan clearly identifies a sharply demarcated cystic lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe essential diagnostic component of an \u003Cstrong\u003Eangiomyolipoma\u003C/strong\u003E (AML) is the presence of fat within the lesion. This lesion is homogenous and hypoechoic, and there is no fat contained within it. 5% of AMLs contain no fat and percutaneous needle biopsy should be performed to confirm the diagnosis. An AML is unlikely in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENephroblastoma\u003C/strong\u003E (Wilms tumour) is the most common renal malignancy in children, with a peak incidence between 2-5 years of age. It typically presents as an abdominal mass. Given this patient\u0027s age and the radiological features, nephroblastoma is not a likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Simple renal cysts tend to be large, unilateral, and solitary with well-defined features."],"references":["Kruskal J, Jerome J. Simple and complex kidney cysts in adults. In: Uptodate. 2021. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/simple-and-complex-kidney-cysts-in-adults","H\u00e9l\u00e9non O, Crosnier A, Verkarre V, Merran S, M\u00e9jean A, Correas JM. Simple and complex renal cysts in adults: Classification system for renal cystic masses. Diagn Interv Imaging. 2018;99(4):189-218. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29482969/","Leslie SW, Sajjad H, Murphy PB. Wilms Tumor. [Updated 2023 May 30]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK442004/","Torres V, York P. Renal angiomyolipomas. In: Uptodate [online]. 2021. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/renal-angiomyolipomas-amls-epidemiology-pathogenesis-clinical-manifestations-and-diagnosis","Choi JH, Ro JY. Retroperitoneal Sarcomas: An Update on the Diagnostic Pathology Approach. Diagnostics (Basel). 2020 Aug 27;10(9):642. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7555595/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41497"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1370"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"13433"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"13433","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/13433"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ed7368ad-8f60-4b00-851d-97a4fbbbbd37.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ed7368ad-8f60-4b00-851d-97a4fbbbbd37.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":457,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41497"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T20:53:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-18T20:53:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1370"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55948"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"3